  33. /* Header format for the "small" model: 20 bytes
  34.        0   "small" magic number
  35.        4   length of marshaled data, in bytes
  36.        8   number of shared blocks
  37.       12   size in words when read on a 32-bit platform
  38.       16   size in words when read on a 64-bit platform
  39.    The 4 numbers are 32 bits each, in big endian.

  41.    Header format for the "big" model: 32 bytes
  42.        0   "big" magic number
  43.        4   four reserved bytes, currently set to 0
  44.        8   length of marshaled data, in bytes
  45.       16   number of shared blocks
  46.       24   size in words when read on a 64-bit platform
  47.    The 3 numbers are 64 bits each, in big endian.

  49.   Header format for the "compressed" model: 10 to 55 bytes
  50.        0   "compressed" magic number
  51.        4   low 6 bits: total size of the header
  52.            high 2 bits: reserved, currently 0
  53.        5 and following
  54.            5 variable-length integers, in VLQ format (1 to 10 bytes each)
  55.            - length of compressed marshaled data, in bytes
  56.            - length of uncompressed marshaled data, in bytes
  57.            - number of shared blocks
  58.            - size in words when read on a 32-bit platform
  59.            - size in words when read on a 64-bit platform

  61.   VLQ format is one or several bytes like 1xxxxxxx 1yyyyyyy 0zzzzzzz.
  62.   First bytes have top bit 1, last byte has top bit 0.
  63.   Each byte carries 7 bits of the number.
  64.   Bytes come in big-endian order: xxxxxxx are the 7 high-order bits,
  65.   zzzzzzzz the 7 low-order bits.
  66. */

  68. ‌#define MAX_INTEXT_HEADER_SIZE 55
